<HEADLINE>
<P>
CLARIFICATION NEEDED ON AVOCADOS, CANCER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As president of the California Avocado Commission, which represents the nearly 
7,000 growers in the state, I am writing to express our deep dissatisfaction 
and concern about your article that erroneously linked avocados with certain 
types of cancer ("Links Between Cancer, Dietary Fat Increase," June 26). 
</P>
<P>
In your article, you state that there is "a strong connection between dietary 
fat -- found in such goodies as ice cream and avocados -- in particular types 
of cancers. . ." By singling out the avocado, you incorrectly inferred that 
eating avocados can potentially cause cancer. 
</P>
<P>
Your misleading reference to avocados has alarmed consumers, many of whom have 
contacted our offices for clarification of your article. 
</P>
<P>
Your unfortunate choice of the avocado as a potentially detrimental food will 
undoubtedly have a negative impact on consumers' perception of a fruit that has 
many nutritional benefits when included in a healthful, well-balanced diet. 
California avocados are cholesterol-free, low in sodium and an excellent source 
of vitamins and potassium. 
</P>
<P>
We want to make it clear to your readers that avocados are healthful and 
nutritious. 
</P>
<P>
MARK AFFLECK 
</P>
<P>
president, California Avocado Commission 
</P>
</TEXT>
