<HEADLINE>
<P>
CSUN OFFICIAL NOT SURPRISED BY MILKE'S EXIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN ORTEGA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Leslie Milke might have surprised some people when she resigned as coach of the 
Cal State Northridge women's basketball team last Friday, but CSUN Associate 
Athletic Director Judy Brame was not caught off guard. 
</P>
<P>
"(Milke) has been thinking about it for the last three years," Brame said 
Thursday. "She enjoyed coaching, but she knew she did not want to spend the 
rest of her life doing it. 
</P>
<P>
"She really loves teaching and I think she wanted to concentrate more on that." 
</P>
<P>
Milke's resignation came a little more than four months before the start of the 
1990-91 season, Northridge's first at the NCAA Division I level. 
</P>
<P>
"I think she just wanted to make sure that this was what she really wanted to 
do," said Brame, who coached Milke when she played for Northridge from 1975-79. 
"I'm sure she didn't want to make a quick decision, then regret it. I think it 
was a good time and a good decision for her." 
</P>
<P>
Milke, who could not be reached for comment, compiled a 100-94 record during 
seven years as coach. She was a Northridge assistant from 1980-83. 
</P>
<P>
After posting a school-record 22-9 mark in 1988-89, Northridge was hit hard by 
injuries last season and finished 11-18. 
</P>
<P>
Milke, a part-time physical education and kinesiology teacher at Northridge, 
was honored as the California Collegiate Athletic Assn. Coach of the Year after 
the 1985-86 and '88-89 seasons, and was the District VIII Coach of the Year for 
'85-86. 
</P>
<P>
As a player, she was an All-CCAA selection as a senior in 1979, and ranks sixth 
on the all-time Northridge career scoring list with 910 points. 
</P>
<P>
A nationwide search for her successor will start shortly, according to Brame, 
who coached Northridge from 1974-79 and again from 1980-83. 
</P>
<P>
Northridge will accept applications until July 30, and hopes to make a hire 
before the fall semester starts on Sept. 3. 
</P>
<P>
"It's hard for me to imagine (Milke) not having some association with the 
team," Brame said. "But I think she made the right decision." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA070690-0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 243502 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 6, 1990, Friday, Valley Edition 
