<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOSPITAL CITES NURSE ERROR IN PATIENT DEATH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DAVID WILLMAN and LANIE JONES, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
FOUNTAIN VALLEY 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Garden Grove woman suffering from advanced breast cancer died last November 
after a nurse at FHP Hospital in Fountain Valley grabbed the wrong medication 
from a shelf and mistakenly administered a lethal dose of potassium chloride, 
FHP officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
"This was an egregious error on the part of the nurse and an inexcusable lapse 
in judgment," FHP said in a written statement, adding that the nurse was 
suspended immediately and fired a week later "as a result of her mistake." 
</P>
<P>
On that same date, Nov. 21, 1989, FHP said that it notified the California 
Board of Registered Nurses of "the termination and the medication error." 
</P>
<P>
The nurse, Maureen Daubert, could not be located Thursday for comment. 
</P>
<P>
Francis J. Johnson, 74, died on Nov. 14, 1989, one day after paramedics brought 
her to FHP in what a hospital official described as a "semi-comatose" 
condition. Johnson, according to FHP, "was an end-stage victim of cancer who . 
. . was expected to die within a short period of time." 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Gary E. Goldstein, a regional vice president for the health maintenance 
organization, said that Johnson had "perked up" the morning of Nov. 14. But by 
that afternoon, Goldstein said in an interview, Johnson's condition was listed 
as "extremely poor" and her doctor prescribed the diuretic Lasix to maintain 
her blood pressure. 
</P>
<P>
Nurse Daubert, Goldstein said, walked to the shelf where medication is kept 
and, instead of removing Lasix, mistakenly grabbed "KCl" -- the chemical 
abbreviation for potassium chloride. 
</P>
<P>
"The (doctor's) order was written for Lasix," Goldstein said. "The error is 
such that we viewed it as totally accidental -- an extreme medication error. A 
one-time event." 
</P>
<P>
Goldstein said that as soon as Daubert realized her error, she and others tried 
immediately but unsuccessfully to revive Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to firing Daubert, Goldstein said the hospital also has relocated 
the potassium chloride to prevent the mistake from happening again because of 
the alphabetical proximity. Goldstein said FHP will continue to investigate the 
incident. 
</P>
<P>
The statements by FHP officials came on the same day that the Orange County 
coroner's office formally amended Johnson's death certificate to "acute 
potassium intoxication." The original certificate, signed by Dr. Sabry Fahmy 
Ghaly, attributed the death to Johnson's "metastatic breast cancer." 
</P>
<P>
Investigators began looking into the woman's death last month after state 
officials were contacted by an FHP employee, Fountain Valley Police 
Investigator Steve Williams said. When deaths occur because of unnatural 
causes, California law requires hospitals to notify local coroners so that 
autopsies may be performed. 
</P>
<P>
In its statement on Thursday, FHP said its ongoing "internal review" has found 
it "difficult to determine Mrs. Johnson's exact cause of death because any one 
of several acute problems could have been at fault, including septic shock, 
massive heart failure, and terminal cancer beyond treatment." 
</P>
<P>
As to the issue of FHP not reporting Johnson's death to the coroner for 
possible autopsy, Goldstein said there was no effort to hide the mistaken dose 
of potassium chloride. Based on his and an FHP lawyer's questioning of four 
doctors and four nurses involved, Goldstein said that Johnson's grave condition 
because of cancer weighed heavily. 
</P>
<P>
"The universal feeling was, the death seemed so obvious to us (because of 
Johnson's cancer and its complications) it never crossed their minds to make it 
a coroner's case. Half said, 'Gee, maybe we should have.' And half said, 'Gee, 
I don't know. . . .' It didn't cross their mind, unfortunately." 
</P>
<P>
Bruce Lyle, a supervising deputy coroner, said that Johnson's death certificate 
was amended Thursday to reflect what his office believes to be the woman's true 
cause of death. Asked if FHP officials should have reported Johnson's death for 
a possible autopsy by the coroner's office last November, Lyle said: 
</P>
<P>
"Absolutely. It would have been autopsied at that time. . . . We can't do 
anything until the case has been reported to us." 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ghaly, who signed the original death certificate attributing Johnson's 
death to her metastatic, or spreading, breast cancer, declined to be 
interviewed and referred a reporter to FHP's public information office. 
Goldstein said that contacting the coroner's office is usually the 
responsibility of FHP's nursing staff. 
</P>
<P>
Johnson, who is survived by her husband and three children, died on Nov. 14 at 
5:50 p.m. -- 40 minutes after nurse Daubert administered the potassium, 
according to Lyle, the deputy coroner. 
</P>
<P>
Based on a review of hospital records and interviews conducted by state medical 
investigators, Lyle said, the coroner's office determined that Johnson's death 
was "accidental." 
</P>
<P>
Garry Garcia, a son of Johnson, said Thursday that he was puzzled about how his 
mother died and the handling of the original death certificate. Garcia said his 
family did not learn of the mistaken potassium dosage until a coroner's 
official called June 4. 
</P>
<P>
Asked about that, the FHP's Goldstein said, "I don't know for sure what was 
said or what wasn't said." 
</P>
<P>
Fountain Valley Police Sgt. Williams said the circumstances surrounding 
Johnson's death, including the hospital's failure to notify the coroner of the 
potassium overdose, remain under investigation. Williams said he plans to 
present his findings to the district attorney's office later this month. 
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Daubert remains under scrutiny from the California Board of 
Registered Nursing, according to Susan Brank, the board's assistant executive 
officer. Brank said that the board, which controls the licensing of nurses, has 
been examining Daubert since January. 
</P>
<P>
But Brank said that, contrary to earlier, erroneous statements by police, 
Daubert's license has not been revoked and has been in good standing since she 
began working in California in September, 1981. Brank declined to say what the 
board has learned during its five months of investigation or what prompted the 
inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
FHP said its notification to the board last November started the investigation 
and that FHP doctors and nurses "have cooperated fully." 
</P>
<P>
According to officials with Fountain Valley police and the coroner's office, 
Daubert had been questioned as of Thursday by only the state nursing board. 
Investigators say they believe she has moved out of state. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Thomas A. Raffin, chief of respiratory medicine at the Stanford University 
School of Medicine, said that an infusion of potassium would typically follow a 
treatment with Lasix because the diruetic flushes the body of a number of 
nutrients and minerals. 
</P>
<P>
"If the level of potassium in the blood falls, it can cause the heart to have a 
bad rhythm, which can result in death," said Raffin. On the other hand, Raffin 
said, a hyper-elevated level of potassium can stop the heart, also causing 
death. 
</P>
<P>
In Johnson's case, the administering of potassium before, instead of after, the 
Lasix, proved deadly. Deputy Coroner Lyle said that Johnson's amended 
certificate of death lists the cause as "cardiac arrhythmia due to hyper 
kalemia." In lay terms, Lyle said, "it means too much potassium in the blood 
system." 
</P>
<P>
Times staff writer Marla Cone contributed to this report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Full Run 
</P>
