WESTINGHOUSE WINS FEDERAL SUIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PHILADELPHIA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Westinghouse Electric Co., which offered to settle an age discrimination 
lawsuit two years ago for $35 million, has won the case in federal appeals 
court. 
</P>
<P>
The ruling Thursday, prompted by a recent U.S. Supreme Court decision, ended 
the court battle that began in 1983 when the federal Equal Employment 
Opportunity Commission challenged Westinghouse for forcing laid-off employees 
to retire before age 70 because severance pay was not available. 
</P>
<P>
The settlement offer, which would have given about 4,000 retirees an average 
payment of $8,750, was rejected by government lawyers because they believed the 
workers would get more in court. 
</P>
